    <!-- Major Arcana Section -->
    <section>
        <h2 class="section-title"><i class="fas fa-crown"></i> Major Arcana</h2>
        <div class="section-content">
            <p>The Major Arcana consists of 22 cards that represent significant life lessons, spiritual journeys, and major events. These cards deal with the core themes of human experience. Here’s a brief overview of the Major Arcana cards:</p>
            <ul class="list-group">
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Fool:</strong> Represents new beginnings, innocence, and taking a leap of faith.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Magician:</strong> Symbolizes personal power, manifestation, and the ability to create reality.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The High Priestess:</strong> Represents intuition, hidden knowledge, and the subconscious mind.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Empress:</strong> Represents nurturing, abundance, and fertility, both literal and metaphorical.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Emperor:</strong> Symbolizes structure, authority, and leadership.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Hierophant:</strong> Represents tradition, spiritual guidance, and mentorship.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Lovers:</strong> Represents love, union, and important life choices.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Chariot:</strong> Symbolizes victory, determination, and control over challenges.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Strength:</strong> Represents courage, inner strength, and self-discipline.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Hermit:</strong> Represents introspection, solitude, and spiritual search for truth.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Wheel of Fortune:</strong> Symbolizes cycles, destiny, and turning points in life.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Justice:</strong> Represents fairness, balance, and truth.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Hanged Man:</strong> Symbolizes letting go, surrender, and seeing things from a new perspective.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Death:</strong> Represents transformation, endings, and new beginnings.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Temperance:</strong> Represents balance, moderation, and harmony.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Devil:</strong> Symbolizes temptation, materialism, and feeling trapped.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Tower:</strong> Represents sudden change, upheaval, and breaking down of false structures.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Star:</strong> Symbolizes hope, inspiration, and spiritual guidance.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Moon:</strong> Represents illusion, intuition, and hidden fears.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Sun:</strong> Symbolizes joy, success, and positivity.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Judgment:</strong> Represents awakening, transformation, and self-reflection.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The World:</strong> Symbolizes completion, fulfillment, and the end of a cycle.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Minor Arcana Section -->
    <section>
        <h2 class="section-title"><i class="fas fa-deck"></i> Minor Arcana</h2>
        <div class="section-content">
            <p>The Minor Arcana consists of 56 cards, divided into four suits. These cards represent the day-to-day experiences and situations we face. Each suit has 14 cards, including numbered cards and court cards (Page, Knight, Queen, and King). Here’s an overview of the four suits and their meanings:</p>
            <ul class="list-group">
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Wands:</strong> Represents action, inspiration, and creativity. Associated with the element of Fire.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Cups:</strong> Represents emotions, relationships, and intuition. Associated with the element of Water.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Swords:</strong> Represents intellect, conflict, and communication. Associated with the element of Air.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Coins/Pentacles:</strong> Represents material world, career, and physical reality. Associated with the element of Earth.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Court Cards Section -->
    <section>
        <h2 class="section-title"><i class="fas fa-users"></i> Court Cards</h2>
        <div class="section-content">
            <p>The Court Cards represent the people or personalities that we encounter in life. Each suit has four court cards: Page, Knight, Queen, and King. These cards often reflect stages of personal development or characteristics of individuals who influence your situation. Here’s a breakdown:</p>
            <ul class="list-group">
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Page:</strong> Represents youthful energy, new beginnings, and curiosity. Pages can also indicate a messenger bringing new information.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Knight:</strong> Represents action, movement, and pursuit of goals. Knights are dynamic, ambitious, and often represent a person who is actively pursuing something.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Queen:</strong> Represents nurturing, emotional depth, and inner wisdom. Queens are caring, compassionate, and intuitive.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>King:</strong> Represents leadership, authority, and mastery. Kings are mature, confident, and possess great control over their realm.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Advanced Tarot Spreads Section -->
    <section>
        <h2 class="section-title"><i class="fas fa-th-large"></i> Advanced Tarot Spreads</h2>
        <div class="section-content">
            <p>For those who have practiced Tarot for a while, using more complex and detailed spreads can provide deeper insights into specific situations. Here are a few advanced spreads:</p>
            <ul class="list-group">
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Grand Tableau:</strong> A large spread using all 78 cards. This spread offers a comprehensive look at all areas of life and is best used for in-depth readings.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Star Spread:</strong> A spread focusing on the future, offering guidance on the steps to take towards achieving your goals. The central card represents the guiding star, and surrounding cards show challenges and advice.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Past, Present, Future Spread:</strong> A variation of the traditional three-card spread, but with more cards to explore each area in greater depth.</li>
                <li class="list-group-item"><strong>The Relationship Spread:</strong> An in-depth spread to explore the dynamics between two people, revealing strengths, challenges, and growth potential.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Conclusion Section -->
    <section>
        <h2 class="section-title"><i class="fas fa-book-open"></i> Conclusion</h2>
        <div class="section-content">
            <p>Tarot is an ancient art that provides valuable insight into the hidden layers of the human experience. Whether you're seeking answers to life's big questions or simply looking to understand your subconscious better, Tarot can serve as a mirror to your soul. While it is not a tool for predicting the future with absolute certainty, it can offer guidance, encouragement, and perspective to help you navigate life's journey. Remember, the power of Tarot lies in the way you interpret its symbols and messages.</p>
        </div>
    </section>
